{"title_page": "WZRD (album)", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|The Wizrd}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = WZRD\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[WZRD (band)|WZRD]]\n| cover      = WZRD (WZRD album - cover art).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = February 28, 2012\n| recorded   = 2011\u20132012\n| studio     = {{ubl|Scott's Crib {{nowrap|(New York, New York)}}|The Brewery Recordings {{nowrap|([[Brooklyn, New York]])}}|Wildman`s Tour Bus}}\n| genre      = <!-- Please source genres -->\n| length     = 47:12\n| label      = {{hlist|Wicked Awesome|[[Universal Republic]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Dot da Genius]]|[[Kid Cudi]]}}\n| chronology = [[WZRD (band)|WZRD]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = WZRD\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Brake\n | single1date = January 31, 2012\n | single2     = Teleport 2 Me, Jamie\n | single2date = January 31, 2012\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''WZRD''''' is the [[eponym]]ously titled debut [[studio album]] by [[United States|American]] [[alternative rock]] duo [[WZRD (band)|WZRD]]. It was released on February 28, 2012, via [[Universal Republic Records]], as well as [[Kid Cudi]]'s newly found label imprint, Wicked Awesome Records. The album was supported by the [[Single (music)|singles]] \"Brake\" and \"Teleport 2 Me, Jamie\".\n\n== Background ==\nWZRD's lead singer [[Kid Cudi]], first unveiled the project in January 2011 after returning to [[Twitter]] announcing a new album he was hoping to have out by the summer: \"pushing for a summer release of the wizard album\u2026 wizard is a rock album, no raps, just singing. brand new thing\u2026 workin on some [[Jay-Z|Jay]] and [[Kanye West|'Ye]] shit\u2026 new mixtape ''A Man Named Scott'' thats this summah for all those who fucks with my raps, this is for u since ima be all rocked out with the wizard shit. also its free\u2026 oh and new york catch me if u can, i start filmin \u201c[[How to Make It in America|how to make it]]\u201d in march.\"<ref>[http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/01/27/kid-cudi-announces-new-rock-lp-wizard-fans-weigh-in/ Kid Cudi Announces New Rock LP Wizard: Fans React]</ref><ref>[http://datnewcudi.com/2011/01/26/kid-cudi-re-joins-twitter-as-wizardcud/ Kid Cudi Re-Joins Twitter as @Wizardcud]</ref>\n\nOn May 31, 2011, Cudi released the first offering from his rock band, a song titled \"Perfect Is the Word\". It was the first song Kid Cudi and Dot da Genius worked on for the album.<ref>[http://datnewcudi.com/2011/05/31/2-be-continuum-debutperfect-is-the-word/ 2 Be Continuum ZPerfect is the World Song Sample]</ref> During a Ustream broadcast they revealed a song titled \"Rocket\" and announced it will serve as the second single.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160413200118/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LnnEdeC4PMA ]</ref> On November 10, 2011, Kid Cudi revealed that the only [[guest appearance]] on the album would be Australian indie-rock band [[Empire of the Sun (band)|Empire of the Sun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/134711119662157824 |title=Twitter / ducidni: The only feature on WZRD isssss |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/134711264113983488 |title=Twitter / ducidni: Empire of the Sun :) |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref> On November 18, 2011, Kid Cudi renamed the band once again to 'WZRD' and announced that the album, will be released on his 28th birthday, January 30, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/137538636668346368 |title=Twitter / ducidni: The title of the album is still |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/137538406992449536 |title=Twitter / ducidni: News update! Me and @DotDaGenius |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/137539161665183744 |title=Twitter / ducidni: And heres the biggest news |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref> On November 20 Kid Cudi announced via Twitter that his upcoming album will not contain any [[profanity]] including the use of the word [[nigga]].<ref name=\"hiphopwired\">{{cite web|author=Jason Weintraub |url=http://hiphopwired.com/2011/11/20/kid-cudis-new-album-contains-no-curse-words-and-no-n-words/ |title=Kid Cudi's New Album Will Contain No Curse Words, No N-Words |publisher=HipHopWired.com |date=2011-10-20 |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref> Kid Cudi released \"Brake\", the first offering from the album on November 21, 2011. On December 5, 2011, Kid Cudi released a snippet of \"Teleport 2 Me, Jamie\", the album's [[lead single]].\n\nOn January 4, 2012, Cudi confirmed on Twitter that there will be a [[Concert tour|tour]] for the band in 2012, beginning in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|author=Volledige naam |url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/154734102891868160 |title=Twitter |publisher=Twitter |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref> On January 12, Dot da Genius took to Twitter to announce that he and Cudi decided to push back ''WZRD'' to a February 28 release date: \"Hey guys, WZRD update. Me and Cudi have been working on our debut album and it\u2019s almost near completion. We are in the final stages of mastering but we really had to take time and pay attention to the sonics as this is new territory for us. With that being said, we have decided to change the release date. We are looking roughly at Feb 28th. Y\u2019all know how Cudi is\u2019 and I'm the same way. Everything has to be in place and now it is. I know it's late notice, we were trying to keep the date but got wrapped up making this album perfect for y\u2019all. However, for making you guys wait a little longer we will release \u2018Brake\u2018 & \u2018Teleport 2 Me\u2018 on iTunes on the previously said date. Hopefully that will hold you guys over until the album drops!\"<ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159047493844340736</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159047648509308928</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159047818764496896</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159048247455924224</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159048347578155009</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159048913435893762</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159049165735854080</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159049520553005056</ref>\n\nAccording to Kid Cudi, bands that inspired the album include [[Electric Light Orchestra]], [[Jimi Hendrix]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]] and [[Pink Floyd]].<ref name=\"listeningsession\">{{cite web|author=DP|title=Kid Cudi & Dot Da Genius Host \"WZRD\" Listening Session in LA|url=http://datnewcudi.com/2012/02/14/kid-cudi-dot-da-genius-host-wzrd-listening-session-in-la/|publisher=DatNewCudi|date=February 14, 2012|accessdate=February 20, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219062739/http://datnewcudi.com/2012/02/14/kid-cudi-dot-da-genius-host-wzrd-listening-session-in-la/|archive-date=February 19, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web|author=Chris Payne|title=Kid Cudi, Dot Da Genius Preview 'WZRD' Album in NYC|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/504442/kid-cudi-dot-da-genius-preview-wzrd-album-in-nyc|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=February 24, 2012|accessdate=February 26, 2012}}</ref> On February 23, the entirety of the album was [[Internet leak|leaked]]. The album was the first to be released under Wicked Awesome Records, a new imprint Kid Cudi had announced in April 2011, in conjunction with [[Kanye West]]'s [[G.O.O.D. Music]] label and Universal Republic.<ref>http://hiphopwired.com/2013/04/04/kid-cudi-focusing-on-wicked-awesome-label-after-leaving-g-o-o-d-music-listen/</ref><ref>http://theversed.com/2013/04/04/kid-cudi-planning-to-focus-on-his-wicked-awesome-record-label-following-g-o-o-d-music-departure/</ref><ref>http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/502560/kid-cudi-on-wzrd-chart-success-im-not-out-here-taking-crazy-pills</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n\n=== Recording and production ===\nAt a private listening session in [[Los Angeles]], Dot da Genius acknowledged that he originally wanted to record the album in the best possible studio they could be in, but Cudi interjected saying he believed the album needed a raw and gritty feel which led to recording on the [[tour bus]] and at his home. \"I could have spent tons of money hiring the best people to do everything, but that's not what I\u2019m about\". The album features no [[profanity]], however Kid Cudi didn't originally intend to record the album in that manner: \"I didn\u2019t write this album with the goal of not cursing. It just happened. When you have important things to say you don\u2019t need to swear,\" Cudi informed the crowd. Although the album will not receive an explicit warning, [[Best Buy]] posed a challenge as they did try to claim it contained cursing because of the word \u201c[[Pussy|pussies]]\u201d in the song \"Upper Room\". \"Pussies is a word used when talking about multiple cats,\u201d Cudi told the crowd, \u201cMy daughter watches [[Puss in Boots]], it\u2019s not a swear word\". Cudi said he had [[writer's block]] for almost 5 months because of his new [[sobriety]], something that had never happened to him for such an extended period of time.<ref name=\"listeningsession\"/> Sean F. Martin, formerly of [[Hatebreed]], was the guitarist on \"Where Did You Sleep Last Night\".<ref>https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/174962357775245313</ref>\n\n=== Music and lyrics ===\nThe album begins with \"The Arrival\", an [[instrumental]] track, where Cudi and Dot da Genius showcase their skills. \"Dream Time Machine\" features supporting vocals from Australian indie-rock band [[Empire of the Sun (band)|Empire of the Sun]], as Cudi previously announced they were to be featured on the album. \"Teleport 2 Me, Jamie\", an ode to Cudi's then-girlfriend, features a sample from American [[synthpop]] act [[Desire (band)|Desire]]'s \"Under Your Spell\" (previously included on the soundtrack to the 2011 film ''[[Drive (2011 film)|Drive]]''), serves as the album's [[lead single]] and was released via digital distribution on January 31, 2012. The album's eighth track \"[[Where Did You Sleep Last Night?]]\", is a [[Cover version|cover]] of the same titled song by American rock band and [[grunge]] pioneers [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], who in turn were inspired by blues guitar legend [[Lead Belly]]'s rendition of the [[Traditional music|traditional]] [[folk music|folk]] song. Completing the album is \"Upper Room\", said to be the most uplifting track on the album.<ref name=\"listeningsession\"/> The last song added to the track list however, was \"Dr. Pill\", where Cudi touched on [[antidepressants]]: \"I took a trip on antidepressant lane for a little bit. After the WZRD song \u201cDr. Pill\u201d everyone thought I was talking about [[MDMA|molly]] or [[MDMA#Purity and dosage of \"ecstasy\"|ecstasy]]. But I'm talking about [[Prescription drug|prescription meds]]. I had just gotten a [[Mental health professional|shrink]]. I was having an [[emotional breakdown]] with this breakup. I kept trying different pills for five months. It fucked me up. They weren't working. It was every side effect on the bottle. I couldn't fuck.\"<ref name=\"complexcover\">{{cite news|author=Joe La Puma|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/01/kid-cudi-february-march-2013-cover-story?nocache=1|title=Kid Cudi: Life After Death (2013 Cover Story)|accessdate=17 January 2013|newspaper=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=15 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 50/100<ref name=MC>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/wzrd|title=Metacritic: ''WZRD''|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=Allmusic>{{cite web|last=Jeffries|first=David|title=WZRD - ''WZRD'' - Review |publisher=AllMusic|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/wzrd-r2402852|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> \n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=CoS>{{cite web|last=Kivel|first=Adam|title=Album Review: WZRD \u2013 ''WZRD''|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2012/03/album-review-wzrd-wzrd/|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''DJ Booth''\n| rev3score = 2.9/5<ref name=DJBooth>{{cite web|last=S.|first=Nathan|title=WZRD - ''WZRD'' - Hip Hop Album Review|url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/albums/review/wzrd-wzrd-03041201/|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''HipHopDX''\n| rev4score = 3.88/5<ref name=HipHopDXReview>{{cite web|last=Fairfax|first=Jesse|title=WZRD (Kid Cudi x Dot Da Genius) ''WZRD''|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/album-reviews/id.1843/title.wzrd-kid-cudi-x-dot-da-genius--wzrd|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=NOW>{{cite web|last=Boles|first=Benjamin|title=WZRD _ NOW Magazine|url=http://www.nowtoronto.com/music/discs.cfm?content=185595|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=RollingStone>{{cite web|last=Katucci|first=Nick|title=WZRD - Album Reviews - Rolling Stone|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/wzrd-20120308|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''WZRD'' received generally mixed reviews from [[music criticism|music critic]]s. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[weighted mean]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 50, based on 10 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n\n=== Commercial performance ===\nThe album debuted at number 3 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first-week sales of 66,000 physical and [[Online distribution|digital copies]] in the United States.<ref name=\"HipHopDX\">{{cite web|last=Jacobs|first=Allen|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.18926/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-3-4-2012|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 3/4/2012|work=HipHopDX|publisher=Cheri Media Group|date=March 7, 2012|accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref> The album also debuted on the [[Rock Albums|Top Rock Albums]] and [[Alternative Albums|Top Alternative Albums]] at number one, and at number 9 on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]], respectively. The album to date has sold 84,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.19168/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-3-25-2012|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 3/25/2012|date=March 28, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329214816/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.19168/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-3-25-2012|archive-date=March 29, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nKid Cudi, who has had [[record label|label]] issues in the past, was less than pleased with the support he received from his label [[Universal Republic]], for ''WZRD''. He claimed the album was under shipped and rushed by his [[major record label|major label]] in hopes that Kid Cudi would move on to ''Man on the Moon III'', which led Cudi to let out his frustrations on online social networking service, [[Twitter]]:\n<blockquote>\"Ok so just a heads up, my weak ass label only shipped 55k [[Compact disc|physicals]] cuz they treated this like some indie side project tax right off. So i apologize on behalf of my weak ass major label. And I apologize for the lack of promo, again, my weak ass major label. They tried to rush me thru this so i can just give em another ''MOTM'', but guess what? Fuck that, next album is ''WZRD''. ''MOTM3'' on hold til 2014. who mad??? not me and @[[Dot da Genius|DotDaGenius]] : ) So its def gonna be tough to find one in the stores guys, I\u2019m sorry about that. I gotta go out and find one too, becuz my weak ass label never even gave us a copy of our own album. FAIL!!! Im lettin Universal Republic have it, fuck it. What they gon\u2019 do, spank me?? hahahaha AND Teleport 2 Me, Jamie aint on the radio!!!! like helloooooooooo????? [[Hit single|HIT HIT HIT]]!!!\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ryon|first=Sean|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.18842/title.kid-cudi-lambasts-label-for-under-shipping-physical-copies-of-wzrd|title=Kid CuDi Lambasts Label For Under Shipping Physical Copies Of \"WZRD\"|work=HipHopDX|publisher=Cheri Media Group|date=February 28, 2012|accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Christman|first=Ed|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/503037/kid-cudi-slams-weak-ass-label-over-handling-of-rock-album|title=Kid Cudi Slams 'Weak Ass Label' Over Handling of Rock Album|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=|date=February 29, 2012|accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/photo-gallery/kid-cudi-airs-out-his-weak-label-under-shipping-wzrd-album|title=Kid Cudi Airs Out His \"Weak A** Label\" for Under Shipping WZRD Album|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|publisher=|date=February 29, 2012|accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = [[WZRD (band)|WZRD]], except where noted\n| total_length    = 47:12\n| title1          = The Arrival\n| length1         = 2:51 \n| title2          = High Off Life\n| length2         = 5:13\n| title3          = The Dream Time Machine\n| note3           = featuring [[Empire of the Sun (band)|Empire of the Sun]]\n| length3         = 4:47\n| title4          = Love Hard\n| length4         = 4:37\n| title5          = Live & Learn\n| length5         = 4:34\n| title6          = Brake\n| length6         = 5:04\n| title7          = Teleport 2 Me, Jamie\n| note7           = John Padgett, WZRD\n| length7         = 3:58\n| title8          = [[Where Did You Sleep Last Night?]]\n| note8           = traditional song\n| length8         = 4:13\n| title9          = Efflictim\n| length9         = 4:27\n| title10         = Dr. Pill\n| length10        = 4:12\n| title11         = Upper Room\n| length11        = 3:12\n| note11          = P. Brown, J. Bruce, WZRD\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits for ''WZRD'' adapted from [[AllMusic]].<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite AV media notes |title=WZRD |others=[[WZRD (band)|WZRD]] |year=2012 |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/wzrd-r2402852/credits |publisher=[[Universal Republic Records]]}}</ref>\n\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n*[[Virgil Abloh]] \u2013 cover design\n*Jennifer Beal \u2013 producer\n*P. Brown \u2013 composer\n*J. Bruce \u2013 composer\n*Sandy Brummels \u2013 director\n*Chris Gehringer \u2013 mastering\n*Dot da Genius \u2013 bass, drums, keyboards, mixing, percussion\n*Larry Gold \u2013 conductor, string arrangements\n*Noah Goldstein \u2013 audio engineer, mixing\n*Kid Cudi \u2013 drums, guitar, keyboards, percussion\n*Kyledidthis \u2013 design, photography\n*Pamela Littky \u2013 photography\n{{col-2}}\n*Nick Littlemore \u2013 sound design\n*Sean F. Martin \u2013 guitar\n*Scott Mescudi \u2013 executive producer\n*O. Omishore \u2013 composer, engineer\n*Oladipo O. Omishore \u2013 executive producer\n*John Padgett \u2013 composer\n*Michael Riley \u2013 engineer\n*Luke Steele \u2013 sound design\n*Howie Weinberg \u2013 mastering\n*WZRD \u2013 art direction, design, producer\n*Billy Zarro \u2013 marketing, product manager\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Chart (2012)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardCanada|9|artist=WZRD|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Billboard200|3|artist=WZRD|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardAlternative|1|artist=WZRD|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardRock|1|artist=WZRD|rowheader=true|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.complex.com/music/2012/02/the-making-of-wzrd/ The Making of WZRD] at ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]''\n\n{{Kid Cudi}}\n\n[[Category:2012 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Universal Republic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Kid Cudi albums]]\n[[Category:WZRD (band) albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dot da Genius]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|The Wizrd}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = WZRD\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[WZRD (band)|WZRD]]\n| cover      = WZRD (WZRD album - cover art).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = February 28, 2012\n| recorded   = 2011\u20132012\n| studio     = {{ubl|Scott's Crib {{nowrap|(New York, New York)}}|The Brewery Recordings {{nowrap|([[Brooklyn, New York]])}}|Wildman`s Tour Bus}}\n| genre      = <!-- Please source genres -->\n| length     = 47:12\n| label      = {{hlist|Wicked Awesome|[[Universal Republic]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Dot da Genius]]|[[Kid Cudi]]}}\n| chronology = [[WZRD (band)|WZRD]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = WZRD\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Brake\n | single1date = January 31, 2012\n | single2     = Teleport 2 Me, Jamie\n | single2date = January 31, 2012\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''WZRD''''' is the [[eponym]]ously titled debut [[studio album]] by [[United States|American]] [[alternative rock]] duo [[WZRD (band)|WZRD]]. It was released on February 28, 2012, via [[Universal Republic Records]], as well as [[Kid Cudi]]'s newly found label imprint, Wicked Awesome Records. The album was supported by the [[Single (music)|singles]] \"Brake\" and \"Teleport 2 Me, Jamie\".\n\n== Background ==\nWZRD's lead singer [[Kid Cudi]], first unveiled the project in January 2011 after returning to [[Twitter]] announcing a new album he was hoping to have out by the summer: \"pushing for a summer release of the wizard album\u2026 wizard is a rock album, no raps, just singing. brand new thing\u2026 workin on some [[Jay-Z|Jay]] and [[Kanye West|'Ye]] shit\u2026 new mixtape ''A Man Named Scott'' thats this summah for all those who fucks with my raps, this is for u since ima be all rocked out with the wizard shit. also its free\u2026 oh and new york catch me if u can, i start filmin \u201c[[How to Make It in America|how to make it]]\u201d in march.\"<ref>[http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/01/27/kid-cudi-announces-new-rock-lp-wizard-fans-weigh-in/ Kid Cudi Announces New Rock LP Wizard: Fans React]</ref><ref>[http://datnewcudi.com/2011/01/26/kid-cudi-re-joins-twitter-as-wizardcud/ Kid Cudi Re-Joins Twitter as @Wizardcud]</ref>\n\nOn May 31, 2011, Cudi released the first offering from his rock band, a song titled \"Perfect Is the Word\". It was the first song Kid Cudi and Dot da Genius worked on for the album.<ref>[http://datnewcudi.com/2011/05/31/2-be-continuum-debutperfect-is-the-word/ 2 Be Continuum ZPerfect is the World Song Sample]</ref> During a Ustream broadcast they revealed a song titled \"Rocket\" and announced it will serve as the second single.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160413200118/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LnnEdeC4PMA ]</ref> On November 10, 2011, Kid Cudi revealed that the only [[guest appearance]] on the album would be Australian indie-rock band [[Empire of the Sun (band)|Empire of the Sun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/134711119662157824 |title=Twitter / ducidni: The only feature on WZRD isssss |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/134711264113983488 |title=Twitter / ducidni: Empire of the Sun :) |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref> On November 18, 2011, Kid Cudi renamed the band once again to 'WZRD' and announced that the album, will be released on his 28th birthday, January 30, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/137538636668346368 |title=Twitter / ducidni: The title of the album is still |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/137538406992449536 |title=Twitter / ducidni: News update! Me and @DotDaGenius |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/137539161665183744 |title=Twitter / ducidni: And heres the biggest news |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref> On November 20 Kid Cudi announced via Twitter that his upcoming album will not contain any [[profanity]] including the use of the word [[nigga]].<ref name=\"hiphopwired\">{{cite web|author=Jason Weintraub |url=http://hiphopwired.com/2011/11/20/kid-cudis-new-album-contains-no-curse-words-and-no-n-words/ |title=Kid Cudi's New Album Will Contain No Curse Words, No N-Words |publisher=HipHopWired.com |date=2011-10-20 |accessdate=2012-01-05}}</ref> Kid Cudi released \"Brake\", the first offering from the album on November 21, 2011. On December 5, 2011, Kid Cudi released a snippet of \"Teleport 2 Me, Jamie\", the album's [[lead single]].\n\nOn January 4, 2012, Cudi confirmed on Twitter that there will be a [[Concert tour|tour]] for the band in 2012, beginning in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|author=Volledige naam |url=https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/154734102891868160 |title=Twitter |publisher=Twitter |date= |accessdate=2013-04-01}}</ref> On January 12, Dot da Genius took to Twitter to announce that he and Cudi decided to push back ''WZRD'' to a February 28 release date: \"Hey guys, WZRD update. Me and Cudi have been working on our debut album and it\u2019s almost near completion. We are in the final stages of mastering but we really had to take time and pay attention to the sonics as this is new territory for us. With that being said, we have decided to change the release date. We are looking roughly at Feb 28th. Y\u2019all know how Cudi is\u2019 and I\u2019m the same way. Everything has to be in place and now it is. I know it\u2019s late notice, we were trying to keep the date but got wrapped up making this album perfect for y\u2019all. However for making you guys wait a little longer we will release \u2018Brake\u2018 & \u2018Teleport 2 Me\u2018 on iTunes on the previously said date. Hopefully that will hold you guys over until the album drops!\"<ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159047493844340736</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159047648509308928</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159047818764496896</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159048247455924224</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159048347578155009</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159048913435893762</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159049165735854080</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/DotDaGenius/status/159049520553005056</ref>\n\nAccording to Kid Cudi, bands that inspired the album include [[Electric Light Orchestra]], [[Jimi Hendrix]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]] and [[Pink Floyd]].<ref name=\"listeningsession\">{{cite web|author=DP|title=Kid Cudi & Dot Da Genius Host \"WZRD\" Listening Session in LA|url=http://datnewcudi.com/2012/02/14/kid-cudi-dot-da-genius-host-wzrd-listening-session-in-la/|publisher=DatNewCudi|date=February 14, 2012|accessdate=February 20, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219062739/http://datnewcudi.com/2012/02/14/kid-cudi-dot-da-genius-host-wzrd-listening-session-in-la/|archive-date=February 19, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web|author=Chris Payne|title=Kid Cudi, Dot Da Genius Preview 'WZRD' Album in NYC|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/photos/live/504442/kid-cudi-dot-da-genius-preview-wzrd-album-in-nyc|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=February 24, 2012|accessdate=February 26, 2012}}</ref> On February 23, the entirety of the album was [[Internet leak|leaked]]. The album was the first to be released under Wicked Awesome Records, a new imprint Kid Cudi had announced in April 2011, in conjunction with [[Kanye West]]'s [[G.O.O.D. Music]] label and Universal Republic.<ref>http://hiphopwired.com/2013/04/04/kid-cudi-focusing-on-wicked-awesome-label-after-leaving-g-o-o-d-music-listen/</ref><ref>http://theversed.com/2013/04/04/kid-cudi-planning-to-focus-on-his-wicked-awesome-record-label-following-g-o-o-d-music-departure/</ref><ref>http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/502560/kid-cudi-on-wzrd-chart-success-im-not-out-here-taking-crazy-pills</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n\n=== Recording and production ===\nAt a private listening session in [[Los Angeles]], Dot da Genius acknowledged that he originally wanted to record the album in the best possible studio they could be in, but Cudi interjected saying he believed the album needed a raw and gritty feel which led to recording on the [[tour bus]] and at his home. \"I could have spent tons of money hiring the best people to do everything, but that's not what I\u2019m about\". The album features no [[profanity]], however Kid Cudi didn't originally intend to record the album in that manner: \"I didn\u2019t write this album with the goal of not cursing. It just happened. When you have important things to say you don\u2019t need to swear,\" Cudi informed the crowd. Although the album will not receive an explicit warning, [[Best Buy]] posed a challenge as they did try to claim it contained cursing because of the word \u201c[[Pussy|pussies]]\u201d in the song \"Upper Room\". \"Pussies is a word used when talking about multiple cats,\u201d Cudi told the crowd, \u201cMy daughter watches [[Puss in Boots]], it\u2019s not a swear word\". Cudi said he had [[writer's block]] for almost 5 months because of his new [[sobriety]], something that had never happened to him for such an extended period of time.<ref name=\"listeningsession\"/> Sean F. Martin, formerly of [[Hatebreed]], was the guitarist on \"Where Did You Sleep Last Night\".<ref>https://twitter.com/wizardcud/status/174962357775245313</ref>\n\n=== Music and lyrics ===\nThe album begins with \"The Arrival\", an [[instrumental]] track, where Cudi and Dot da Genius showcase their skills. \"Dream Time Machine\" features supporting vocals from Australian indie-rock band [[Empire of the Sun (band)|Empire of the Sun]], as Cudi previously announced they were to be featured on the album. \"Teleport 2 Me, Jamie\", an ode to Cudi's then-girlfriend, features a sample from American [[synthpop]] act [[Desire (band)|Desire]]'s \"Under Your Spell\" (previously included on the soundtrack to the 2011 film ''[[Drive (2011 film)|Drive]]''), serves as the album's [[lead single]] and was released via digital distribution on January 31, 2012. The album's eighth track \"[[Where Did You Sleep Last Night?]]\", is a [[Cover version|cover]] of the same titled song by American rock band and [[grunge]] pioneers [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], who in turn were inspired by blues guitar legend [[Lead Belly]]'s rendition of the [[Traditional music|traditional]] [[folk music|folk]] song. Completing the album is \"Upper Room\", said to be the most uplifting track on the album.<ref name=\"listeningsession\"/> The last song added to the track list however, was \"Dr. Pill\", where Cudi touched on [[antidepressants]]: \"I took a trip on antidepressant lane for a little bit. After the WZRD song \u201cDr. Pill\u201d everyone thought I was talking about [[MDMA|molly]] or [[MDMA#Purity and dosage of \"ecstasy\"|ecstasy]]. But I\u2019m talking about [[Prescription drug|prescription meds]]. I had just gotten a [[Mental health professional|shrink]]. I was having an [[emotional breakdown]] with this breakup. I kept trying different pills for five months. It fucked me up. They weren\u2019t working. It was every side effect on the bottle. I couldn\u2019t fuck.\"<ref name=\"complexcover\">{{cite news|author=Joe La Puma|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/01/kid-cudi-february-march-2013-cover-story?nocache=1|title=Kid Cudi: Life After Death (2013 Cover Story)|accessdate=17 January 2013|newspaper=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=15 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 50/100<ref name=MC>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/wzrd|title=Metacritic: ''WZRD''|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=Allmusic>{{cite web|last=Jeffries|first=David|title=WZRD - ''WZRD'' - Review |publisher=AllMusic|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/wzrd-r2402852|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref> \n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=CoS>{{cite web|last=Kivel|first=Adam|title=Album Review: WZRD \u2013 ''WZRD''|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2012/03/album-review-wzrd-wzrd/|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''DJ Booth''\n| rev3score = 2.9/5<ref name=DJBooth>{{cite web|last=S.|first=Nathan|title=WZRD - ''WZRD'' - Hip Hop Album Review|url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/albums/review/wzrd-wzrd-03041201/|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''HipHopDX''\n| rev4score = 3.88/5<ref name=HipHopDXReview>{{cite web|last=Fairfax|first=Jesse|title=WZRD (Kid Cudi x Dot Da Genius) ''WZRD''|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/album-reviews/id.1843/title.wzrd-kid-cudi-x-dot-da-genius--wzrd|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]''\n| rev5score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=NOW>{{cite web|last=Boles|first=Benjamin|title=WZRD _ NOW Magazine|url=http://www.nowtoronto.com/music/discs.cfm?content=185595|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev6score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=RollingStone>{{cite web|last=Katucci|first=Nick|title=WZRD - Album Reviews - Rolling Stone|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/wzrd-20120308|accessdate=8 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''WZRD'' received generally mixed reviews from [[music criticism|music critic]]s. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[weighted mean]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 50, based on 10 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n\n=== Commercial performance ===\nThe album debuted at number 3 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first-week sales of 66,000 physical and [[Online distribution|digital copies]] in the United States.<ref name=\"HipHopDX\">{{cite web|last=Jacobs|first=Allen|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.18926/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-3-4-2012|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 3/4/2012|work=HipHopDX|publisher=Cheri Media Group|date=March 7, 2012|accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref> The album also debuted on the [[Rock Albums|Top Rock Albums]] and [[Alternative Albums|Top Alternative Albums]] at number one, and at number 9 on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]], respectively. The album to date has sold 84,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.19168/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-3-25-2012|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 3/25/2012|date=March 28, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329214816/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.19168/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-3-25-2012|archive-date=March 29, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nKid Cudi, who has had [[record label|label]] issues in the past, was less than pleased with the support he received from his label [[Universal Republic]], for ''WZRD''. He claimed the album was under shipped and rushed by his [[major record label|major label]] in hopes that Kid Cudi would move on to ''Man on the Moon III'', which led Cudi to let out his frustrations on online social networking service, [[Twitter]]:\n<blockquote>\"Ok so just a heads up, my weak ass label only shipped 55k [[Compact disc|physicals]] cuz they treated this like some indie side project tax right off. So i apologize on behalf of my weak ass major label. And I apologize for the lack of promo, again, my weak ass major label. They tried to rush me thru this so i can just give em another ''MOTM'', but guess what? Fuck that, next album is ''WZRD''. ''MOTM3'' on hold til 2014. who mad??? not me and @[[Dot da Genius|DotDaGenius]] : ) So its def gonna be tough to find one in the stores guys, I\u2019m sorry about that. I gotta go out and find one too, becuz my weak ass label never even gave us a copy of our own album. FAIL!!! Im lettin Universal Republic have it, fuck it. What they gon\u2019 do, spank me?? hahahaha AND Teleport 2 Me, Jamie aint on the radio!!!! like helloooooooooo????? [[Hit single|HIT HIT HIT]]!!!\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ryon|first=Sean|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.18842/title.kid-cudi-lambasts-label-for-under-shipping-physical-copies-of-wzrd|title=Kid CuDi Lambasts Label For Under Shipping Physical Copies Of \"WZRD\"|work=HipHopDX|publisher=Cheri Media Group|date=February 28, 2012|accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Christman|first=Ed|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/503037/kid-cudi-slams-weak-ass-label-over-handling-of-rock-album|title=Kid Cudi Slams 'Weak Ass Label' Over Handling of Rock Album|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=|date=February 29, 2012|accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/photo-gallery/kid-cudi-airs-out-his-weak-label-under-shipping-wzrd-album|title=Kid Cudi Airs Out His \"Weak A** Label\" for Under Shipping WZRD Album|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|publisher=|date=February 29, 2012|accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = [[WZRD (band)|WZRD]], except where noted\n| total_length    = 47:12\n| title1          = The Arrival\n| length1         = 2:51 \n| title2          = High Off Life\n| length2         = 5:13\n| title3          = The Dream Time Machine\n